# From liminal (etymology: Latin limin-, limen meaning "threshold") and centric (etymology: medieval Latin -centricus < Latin centrum meaning “a central position”).

Configurations in which features such as thresholds (or extremities/edges) simultaneously exhibit attributes of the features of centralisation, and may in fact be one and the same; shapes where extremities may be considered simultaneously as focal points, and as identical to the focal points. 
Examples: 
§	the torus (a three-dimensional doughnut-shaped surface of revolution)
§	a mental illustration to accompany the concept would be to consider a recursive set of Chinese Boxes (i.e. a set of boxes of graduated size, each fitting inside the next larger one)